  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"jump-content\" tabindex=\"-1\"\u003e\n            \n\n    \n    \n\n    \u003carticle\u003e\n\n    \n    \n\n\n\n\n\n    \n\n    \n      \n\n\u003cdiv data-analytics-module=\"{\n    \u0026#34;module_name\u0026#34;: \u0026#34;Hero Menu\u0026#34;,\n    \u0026#34;section_header\u0026#34;: \u0026#34;Celebrate World Quantum Day with this mesmerizing Doodle\u0026#34;\n  }\"\u003e\n      \n      \n        \u003cp\u003e\n          Superposition is a fundamental quantum mechanics concept — and it’s pretty mind-blowing. Today’s Doodle helps us understand it.\n        \u003c/p\u003e\n      \n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \n\n    \n      \u003cdiv\u003e\n      \u003cp\u003e\n        \u003cvideo autoplay=\"\" muted=\"\" loop=\"\" playsinline=\"\" src=\"https://storage.googleapis.com/gweb-uniblog-publish-prod/original_videos/Quantum_Keyword_Hero_Imagery_A_2096x1182.mp4\" title=\"Animation showing the word GOOGLE spelled out using six light blue coin-shaped ornaments hanging vertically by thin red strings. Segments of the letters are rendered in darker blue within the ornaments, which spin to ultimately spell GOOGLE.\" poster=\"\n            \n              https://storage.googleapis.com/gweb-uniblog-publish-prod/original_images/QuantumDoodle_Static_2097x1182_1.png\n            \"\u003e\n          Sorry, your browser doesn\u0026#39;t support embedded videos, but don\u0026#39;t worry, you can\n            \u003ca href=\"https://storage.googleapis.com/gweb-uniblog-publish-prod/original_videos/Quantum_Keyword_Hero_Imagery_A_2096x1182.mp4\"\u003edownload it\u003c/a\u003e\n            and watch it with your favorite video player!\n        \u003c/video\u003e\n      \u003c/p\u003e\n      \n    \u003c/div\u003e\n\n    \n\n    \n    \u003cdiv data-reading-time=\"true\" data-component=\"uni-article-body\"\u003e\n\n            \n              \n\n\n\n\n\n\u003cuni-article-speakable page-title=\"Celebrate World Quantum Day with this mesmerizing Doodle\" listen-to-article=\"Listen to article\" data-date-modified=\"2025-04-14T16:25:57.827002+00:00\" data-tracking-ids=\"G-HGNBTNCHCQ,G-6NKTLKV14N\" data-voice-list=\"en.ioh-pngnat:Cyan,en.usb-pngnat:Lime\" data-script-src=\"https://www.gstatic.com/readaloud/player/web/api/js/api.js\"\u003e\u003c/uni-article-speakable\u003e\n\n            \n\n            \n            \n\n\n  \n    \u003cdiv data-component=\"uni-article-paragraph\" role=\"presentation\" data-analytics-module=\"{\n           \u0026#34;module_name\u0026#34;: \u0026#34;Paragraph\u0026#34;,\n           \u0026#34;section_header\u0026#34;: \u0026#34;Celebrate World Quantum Day with this mesmerizing Doodle\u0026#34;\n         }\"\u003e\n        \u003cp data-block-key=\"1cm3u\"\u003eYou might be wondering why today’s Doodle shows an illustration of quantum superposition. April 14 is World Quantum Day, and this year is also the International Year of Quantum — celebrating 100 years since the discovery of quantum mechanics. And what’s special about quantum mechanics? These are underlying rules for the world around us at the smallest level, including molecules, atoms and subatomic particles. And teams at Google are working on using the same principles to power a computer to advance science and solve problems that are otherwise impossible. So let’s talk more about one of those principles: superposition.\u003c/p\u003e\n      \u003c/div\u003e\n  \n\n  \n    \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\u003cuni-related-content-tout title=\"3 real-world problems that quantum comp…\" cta=\"See more\" summary=\"For World Quantum Day, we’re sharing three real-world ways quantum computers may advance science and benefit people.\" hideimage=\"False\" eyebrow=\"Related Article\" image-alt-text=\"\" role=\"none\" fullurl=\"https://blog.google/technology/research/google-quantum-computer-real-world-applications/\" pagetype=\"articlepage\" isarticlepage=\"\" data-ga4-related-article=\"{\n  \u0026#34;event\u0026#34;: \